# Coding standards and syntax

- Always follow the existing coding style and conventions of the project. Infer style from nearby code (naming, formatting, patterns) and match it.

- Do not introduce new frameworks or major dependencies without explicit approval; prefer the tools and libraries already used in the project.

- Never intentionally return code with syntax errors. Before finalizing any code snippet, check that it is syntactically valid in the target language.

- If you are unsure about syntax or an API, say so and mark the relevant part as [uncertain] rather than guessing.

- When you spot a potential syntax or type error in your own suggestion, correct it and briefly explain the fix.

- For non‑trivial changes, suggest or run appropriate checks (for example: tests, type checker, linter, or build) and mention the commands.